sushy/main.py.message: Why is one entry in registries unconditionally set, while the other is set only if it does not already exist?

The prior code mapped MessageRegistryFile.Registry to the message registry.  The registry names look something like: "iDRAC.1.6.1", "Base.1.5.0", etc.
See: http://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/DSP0266_1.11.0.html#message-object
The new code continues to do that on line 481.
In addition, the new code also maps MessageRegistryFile.Id to the registry.  The Ids look like: "Messages", "BaseMessages", etc.
The resulting dict looks like:
{
  'iDRAC.1.6.1': registry1,
  'Messages': registry1,
  'Base.1.5.0': registry2,
  'BaseMessages': registry2
}
This allows the message parsing code to lookup the registry first by MessageRegistryFile name and then by MessageRegistryFile Id using the same dictionary.
On some BMCs, there potentially could be an issue if there is a registry ID that happens to be the same as a registry name, though this would be very unlikely, as the format of registry names is defined to be <name>.<majorVersion>.<minorVersion>.
The "if" statement makes it so that if the collision does happen, the primary entry in the dict is kept, and the fallback entry is not made, resulting in a dictionary that looks like:
{
  'iDRAC.1.6.1': registry1,
  'Base.1.5.0': registry2,
  'BaseMessages': registry2
}
Thoug, in order for this to happen, the Id for registry1 would have to be 'iDRAC.1.6.1'.
.  This results in no fallback to looking up by the hardcoded 'Messages' or 'BaseMessages' Ids for that message registry.
Note that the registry names and registry Ids are all unique on an iDRAC.
See:
- https://<ip>/redfish/v1/Registries/Messages
- https://<ip>/redfish/v1/Registries/BaseMessages
What is the value of 'r.identity'? Does it meet the needs of the change to sushy/resources/registry/message_registry.py, where it looks through the 'Messages' and 'BaseMessages' registries?

sushy/resources/registry/message_registr.message: I am wondering if a `message_field` can contain a format string and message arguments? If so, the message could be formatted in the absence of registries. That could be implemented by a follow-on change.

A message field may optionally contain a "message" that does not need to be parsed.
It is required that it contain a MessageId that does need to be parsed.  Parsing the message pointed to by the MessageId and doing argument substitution is what this code is all about.
See: http://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/DSP0266_1.11.0.html#message-object
